Korea-Bulgarian Summit to Expand Cooperation in Nuclear Power Plants and Defense Industries (Bulgarian) | Yahoo!
(SEOUL=Yonhap News) South Korean President Moon Jae-in met with Bulgarian Prime Minister Borisov during his official visit to Korea on September 27 and discussed ways to expand bilateral cooperation.
This is the first time the Prime Minister of Bulgaria visited Korea.
President Moon welcomed the visit to Korea prior to the 30th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations next year and appreciated the leadership of Prime Minister Borisov, leading the development of Bulgaria.
The two leaders appreciated the continued increase in trade and investment between the two countries amid the global expansion of protectionism and agreed to work together to expand economic cooperation in the future.
President Moon welcomed Bulgaria's commitment to empower Korean companies to become "strategic investors," and said he hoped that this would help Korean companies to invest in Bulgaria.
He also stressed that South Korea will be the best partner for Bulgaria in the process of introducing nuclear power plants and modernizing defense, and called for attention and cooperation so that Korean companies can participate in the order of the Bulgarian government's nuclear power plants and the promotion of the defense industry.
In addition, the two leaders agreed to strengthen future-oriented cooperation in the areas of battery and auto parts for electric vehicles and renewable energy.
Prime Minister Borisov hoped that close cooperation in ICT (information and communication technology) and science and technology, as well as in education, will be conducted.
He also talked about the Korean Peninsula's peace process, and expressed his gratitude for the support of the Korean government's efforts to establish peace on the Korean Peninsula, including the announcement of a statement by Bulgaria in support of the North-South and North-America Summits.
Prime Minister Borisov appreciated President Moon's will to build a peace regime on the Korean Peninsula and the efforts of the Korean government, and reiterated the firm support of the Bulgarian government.
The meeting was attended by Mr. Sung Yunmo, Secretary of the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy, Mr. Lee Hao-houn, Chief Economic Secretary of the Chong (President's Office), and Mr. Kim Hyun-jong, Second Director of the State Security Office.
On behalf of the Minister of Foreign Affairs, Kang Gyeong-wa (Kang Gyeong-fa) during his visit to the United States, the first official of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Zhao Seong, also attended.
Local industry in Hyogo and Awaji Island, Kinki Ceramics Co., Ltd., which manufactures "Awaji tiles," filed for quasi-self-insolvency debt of approximately 2 billion yen (Imperial Data Bank) - Yahoo!
It was also affected by the sluggish housing market and the frequent earthquake and tsunami that led to the rise in consumer tile roofs.
Kinki Ceramics Co., Ltd. (TDB Corporation Code:53173983, capital of 91.2 million yen, 881-8 Otani, Awaji City, Hyogo Prefecture, representative Yukizo Fukuhara and 44 employees) filed for quasi-self-insolvency at the Kobe District Court on August 30.
The applicant is Daichi Yoshida (1-10-8 Nishitenman, Kita Ward, Osaka City, Osaka Prefecture, and Daichi Yoshida Law Office, telephone 06-6365-6038).
The company was founded in June 1895 and reorganized in April 1961.
At first, he started his business as a manufacturer of ibushi tiles, a local industry in Awaji Island, in Nishitan-cho, Mihara County (present Minamiawaji City) under the trade name of Kinki Kiln Co., Ltd.
In October 1986, Kyowa Kiln Co., Ltd. merged into Kyowa Kiln Co., Ltd. and succeeded the business of Kinki Sangyo Co., Ltd., but at the same time, the head office was moved to its present location after changing its current business name.
After that, sales offices were established in Fukuyama City, Hiroshima City, Oita City, Miyazaki City, etc., and it became the current system, and Ibushi-gawara was mainly used before, but due to changes in consumer needs, Western-style tiles such as flat plate tiles were manufactured at 70% and Ibushi-gawara was manufactured at 30%.
The company has established a wide range of sales bases mainly in western Japan, including major house manufacturers, building materials trading companies, and roof construction companies.
He was well known as the top tile maker of Awaji Island.
However, demand continued to grow due to the sluggish housing market following the Lehman shock and the severe damage caused by the Great East Japan Earthquake and the Kumamoto Earthquake.
On the profit side, in addition to a decline in the profit margin due to the surge in fuel prices, the company suffered a continuous deficit with excessive interest-bearing debt associated with inventory burdens and business fixed investment, and was forced to make severe financial arrangements.
For this reason, the Bank sought to rebuild its business by requesting financial institutions to ease the conditions for repayment of borrowings, but there were no signs of a recovery in business conditions, and the financial position gradually became tight.
I couldn't help but gave up on business continuity and this was the measure.
The debt is currently under investigation, but it is estimated to be about 2 billion yen.
