Prefectural Fishery Federation "Start discussion toward full-scale operation" President Nozaki "Iwaki Minpo Official Website"
With the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant accident at TEPCO, discussions aimed at full-scale operation in each district and other areas regarding the test operation that continues in the fisheries off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture became concrete.
Mr. Tetsu Nozaki said, "As a prefectural fishing association, we need a flow toward full-scale operation, and we want to gather representatives and start discussions."
The Union Presidents' Association also approved the formal addition of casago, sakura trout, and Murasoi off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture to the target species for test operations.
The remaining undisclosed seafood became two fish species: the binosgai and the common casbe.
At the end of the meeting, President Nozaki told reporters that the start of full-scale operations was uncertain.
Regarding the treatment water after purifying contaminated water at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, Mr. Yoshiaki Harada, Minister of the Environment, and Mayor Ichiro Matsui, Mayor of Osaka City, said, "There is a problem with Keren-flavored discussions, and the position of opposition to ocean release remains unchanged."
In discussing the full-scale operation, Akira Egawa, head of Iwaki City Fisheries Cooperative, pointed out that "it is necessary to suck up opinions from the bottom," and said that he respects the wishes of the members.
The Board of Directors meets with a group of branch offices to resolve the problems one by one, and concludes as a city fishing cooperative.
Kanji Tachiya, head of the Soma Futaba Fisheries Cooperative, said, "In addition to the fishermen, it is necessary to discuss with the buyers."
The Soma Futaba Fishery Cooperative is supported by the government, and seven new ships will enter next year.
