"Korea wants to return to GSOMIA" U.S. Undersecretary of State (Sankei Shimbun) - Yahoo!
U.S. Undersecretary of State for South Korea and Japan, Napper, in an interview with the Sankei Shimbun at the U.S. Ambassador's residence in Tokyo, said on November 27 that he hoped that Korea would reconsider and return the decision to destroy Japan and Korea's military information comprehensive protection agreement, which would expire on November 23.
It is unusual for high-ranking U.S. officials to refer to the reconsideration of GSOMIA's destruction.
GSOMIA is based on the agreement between Japan, South Korea, Japan, the United States, and South Korea to share missile launch information.
In August, Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan, and if it expires, the framework for protecting military information will collapse.
Napper argues that without GSOMIA, we cannot effectively respond to the crisis.
"There is time until the revocation," he strongly urged the return of Korea.
He also pointed out that the joint flight training conducted by China and Russia in July over the Sea of Japan was "for the first time in history."
The recent deterioration in Japan-Korea relations has been pointed out as "damaging the national interests of the United States."
"There is no intention of intermediation," he said, "Japan and Korea will play a positive role to fill the gap."
