Tokaimura Critical Accident, 20 years in 30 days 300 nuclear facility troubles: Hokkaido Shimbun
From the following year of the critical accident in Tokai-mura, Ibaraki Prefecture, which was the first fatal accident in the history of nuclear power in Japan, to fiscal 2006, 336 cases of accidents and failures occurred at nuclear facilities nationwide were reported.
20 years in 30 days from the critical accident that alarmed the safety myth of the nuclear industry.
According to the report, although the level 0 (not important for safety) of the international evaluation scale (INES) showing seriousness and about 90% of cases not evaluated are accounted for, it is necessary to raise awareness of safety without hesitation based on lessons learned from the accident and the accident at TEPCO Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station in 11 years.
Mitsukazu Soda, who has completed the story and original drawings of creative picture books and is seeking donations for publication, says on September 18 in Echizen City, Fukui Prefecture.
Koichi Soda (64), an artist in the Echizen City Regional Development Cooperation Volunteer in Fukui Prefecture, started crowdfunding to raise donations online to publish creative picture books inspired by legends in Fukui Prefecture in order to promote town development using picture books.
Mr. Soda, who was originally from Hokkaido and started his activities as a member of the cooperative group from April this year, said, "I want to convey the hearts of the people of Fukui based on deep faith through picture books."
[Donation is here] To convey Fukui's heart.
While Mr. Soda is active as an artist working on contemporary art based on mathematics, he has also been active as a member of the cooperative team since the end of the calendar.
After working on the town development of Nagano, Kumamoto and Tochigi, he joined Echizen City in April this year.
In the same city that produced Satoko KAKO and Chihiro IWASAKI, he aims to create a town using picture books.
Soda lived in the city and said, "I was surprised by the depth of compassion around me for the first time."
What attracted attention was the legend of the city of Awara, "The face of the demon of the bride and daughter."
It is a story that a gentle married woman continues to chant Nenbutsu (Buddhist invocation) to help her mother without worrying about being surprised by her face.
"I forgot my hatred and returned with kindness and kindness, and I felt the origin of the faith and kindness of the people of Fukui."
Inspired by the original picture book, Mr. Soda went to Yoshizaki Gobo in Awara City as soon as he arrived, and he completed the story "Meoto Oni" where a husband and wife of a gentle demon and a boy appeared.
From June, he took advantage of his job to draw 10 scenes with warm watercolors, and the materials of picture books were scattered.
In addition, the cover of picture books will be made of Japanese paper using Echizen Washi, a traditional craft that lives in Echizen City.
This leads to an opportunity for parents and children to enjoy the touch of Japanese paper through reading and listening.
The goal of the donation amount is 850,000 yen for 600 copies.
The deadline is 25 October.
Mr. Soda said, "Fukui's heart, which has been nurtured under the historical Buddhist culture, is proud throughout Japan.
I want to convey the true kindness and compassion that has been handed down to children through picture books."
