Sakura shrimp in the growth process PT such as Shizuoka City, taken 290 meters deep | Shizuoka Shimbun at Ess
Sakura Ebi, born this year, was successfully photographed in the deep sea of Suruga Bay.
The Yuhi Sakura Ebi Project, a project of the Ocean Industry Cluster Council led by industry, academia, and government in Shizuoka City, succeeded in photographing sakura shrimp, which is thought to have been born during the spawning season this spring and summer, at a depth of 290 meters in Suruga Bay.
The video of the growth process is valuable, and the people concerned want to lead to the elucidation of the ecology of sakura shrimp, which has a lot of mysteries.
The photo was taken near the bottom of the sea about 1 to 5 km off the coast of Kamahara district, Shimizu Ward, the city.
A total of 300 were confirmed in 17 minutes.
During the day, the traditional knowledge that sakura shrimp in the deep sea form a certain group at the bottom of the sea was refuted.
The adult body is about 40 mm long, and the individual reflected is about 23 mm long.
The spawning season was identified by matching data from season to season of freshly caught sakura shrimp.
Detailed analysis is requested by Fujitsu Software Technologies and Shizuoka Technical College, which make up the team.
Keisuke Mizuno, Project Leader, said, "I want to capture the living figure of individuals in the growth process, including fry."
Mother Ranch Reopens, Chiba Prefecture People Free Damaged by Typhoon by the end of October | Shizuoka Shimbun
Chiba-kun, the mascot character of Chiba Prefecture, welcomes visitors at the Mother Ranch, which has reopened its business.
Mother Ranch in Futsu City, Chiba Prefecture, which had been closed from 9 days due to power outages and damage to facilities caused by Typhoon No. 15, reopened on 28th.
Residents in Chiba Prefecture will be free to enter by the end of October in order to boost the affected areas.
Many people visited the park at the same time as the opening of the park, and at the entrance gate, the mascot character of the prefecture "Chiba-kun" who ran to support was welcomed.
The roof was covered with blue sheets, and some facilities continued to be repaired, but half of the restaurants began to reopen.
Kenji Mitani (34), a family member of Sagamihara City, said with a smile, "I was worried about when I would resume.I came to enjoy the event of potato digging, thinking that I would be connected to reconstruction."
