Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Gifu Shimbun Web) - Yahoo!News
The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (MAFF) announced on July 27 an amendment to the Anti-Defection Guidelines to prevent the spread of Ton cholera, a domestic infectious disease.
The province will select nine prefectures, including Gifu Prefecture and Aichi Prefecture, where pigs and wild boars have been confirmed to be infected.
Vaccination of live pigs and fertilized eggs is restricted to the region, but distribution outside the meat and processed foods is permitted.
After making public comments to the general public (an open call for opinions), we aim to complete the procedure as early as October.
By using vaccines and allowing extraterrestrial distribution such as meat, it is no longer a "clean country" certified by international organizations and may affect the export of pork.
Since the outbreak of September last year, Japan has been temporarily on hold.
In the revised plan, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries set up a "recommended area for vaccination" based on the opinions of experts regarding areas with high risk of infection from wild boar to pigs.
The target prefecture will create a "vaccination program" that summarizes the scope, time, number of heads, how to proceed, etc., and will be confirmed by the province and allowed to use it at the governor's discretion.
Seven other prefectures in Saitama, Toyama, Ishikawa, Fukui, Nagano, Mie and Shiga have been proposed as recommended areas for vaccination.
When the guidelines have been revised, the region will look at the situation and decide extremely once again.
The movement of inoculated pigs, semen, fertilized eggs, corpses, and excreted objects is limited in principle to the region.
As for meat and processed products, it is not intended based on the cost of distribution restrictions and the impact on farmers, and it practically accepts distribution outside the region.
To prevent viruses from spreading, we will thoroughly process food waste.
He also advocates the safety of inoculated pigs and works to prevent harmful rumors.
The revised guidelines were compiled at an expert meeting held on the same day and confirmed at a meeting of the Anti-Defection Control Headquarters.
In the future, we will conduct opinion inquiries and public comments to prefectures until October 7 and implement new quarantine guidelines.
