Mr. Onsarigo helped Nagai and elementary school students work as pacemaker and three people update the tournament record|Yamagata Shimbun
Children run at 800 meters.
On the left is Joseph Onsarigo, a pacemaker in Nagai City, Japan.
Nagai City Elementary School's Friendship Athletics Tournament was held on the 26th at the city's Koyo Seiki Athlete Field Nagai (city track and field), and Joseph Onsarigo (27) from Kenya, a long-distance runner belonging to Nasu Construction, was a pacemaker.
With a light run, three new records of the tournament were set up.
Onsarigo pulled the children in a total of four races, 1000 meters for men and 800 meters for women.
Tomoya Koseki (Hirano Ko6) was ranked first in the men's competition in 3 minutes and 4 seconds 38, and Ransei Shigara (Isazawa Ko 6) was ranked first in the women's competition in 2 minutes and 34 seconds 17.
Mr. Koseki said, "It was hard to talk about fast Onsarigo players, but I was able to endure it."
Onsarigo said, "The children were good at running, and I had a perfect job."
The competition was organized by the Nagai City Elementary School Sports Promotion Association to encourage sixth graders in the city to deepen their friendship.
